	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Wed, Nov 14th 6:42 PM 2001</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Well, I wasn't really ANNOYED by the fact people use LoH, im just REALLY curious why people use it. It doesn't make sense to me. As you said SoW, well that makes sense. Spirit Of (the) Wolf. They left out a word. But Lay Hands is really the action of Laying Hands ON someone. Therefore it should be LHo or just LH. I just dont get why or how people came up with LoH. Laying on Hands?  And if it IS Lay on OF hands, it still sounds like your performing some ritual in which you lay on your hands until they fall asleep or something. But anyways, back to the SoW thing, that's spirit of the wolf. The people aren't ADDING names, they're subtracting them. By saying Lay ON Hands, you're adding a whole new word that isn't even part of the ability! <br><br>So anyways, I'm not MAD with LoH, that's not the thing, it's that being a paladin, I should know why the heck people call it LoH. <br><br>P.S.: If what you say is true, why havent people started calling Harm Touch, Harm on Touch or something? I dont see HoT, just LoH. And Harm on Touch makes no sense as Lay on Hands doesn't either.<br><br>Gfuais Palais &lt;The Elderblood&gt;<br>Dwarven Paladin of the 40th Season (I can tell it's Summer by the "hotness" of this level)<br>Follower of Brell on Drinal<br><br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
